# Interpreter for _restore1 - Database restoration wrapper
#
# The restore function is a high-level wrapper that orchestrates database restoration
# from dump files. It performs two critical steps:
#   1. Calls init to create database structure (.env/local/ directories)
#   2. Delegates to batch with keep-going mode for fault-tolerant execution
#
# Arguments:
#   $1 - filepath to dump script
#
# Type: Combinator function (outputs commands to be executed)
# Default: sh (execute the init and batch commands)
#
# Execution flow:
#   restore → init (creates structure) → batch (processes dump with keep-going mode)
#
# Why keep-going mode?
#   Restore uses keep-going mode to handle duplicate imports gracefully.
#   If a config already exists, import fails but restore continues with
#   remaining commands (categories, links, sessions).
#
# Usage:
#   vpn-switch dump > backup.sh
#   vpn-switch restore backup.sh            # Full restoration
#
#   env VPN_SWITCH_BASE=/DEST vpn-switch restore /path/to/backup.sh  # Cross-database restore
#
# Override examples:
#   VPN_SWITCH_INTERPRETER_restore=sh       # Default (execute init and batch commands)
#   VPN_SWITCH_INTERPRETER_restore=cat      # Dry-run (show commands without executing)
#
# Important notes:
#   - Takes filepath argument instead of reading from stdin
#   - Always calls init first (required for .env/local/ export statements)
#   - init must run with proper interpreter (sh for execution, not cat)
#   - Path resolution: Uses $VPN_SWITCH_CONTEXT_SCRIPT for absolute path to vpn-switch.sh
#   - Environment isolation: init and batch run in separate subprocess contexts
